5. Roles & Permissions (Aligned with Locked Auth Spec)

EDITOR
	•	Allowed actions:
	•	SITE_EDIT
	•	Can:
	•	Update site settings
	•	Update page content
	•	Cannot:
	•	Publish
	•	Access store/orders/scheduling

ADMIN
	•	Allowed actions:
	•	SITE_EDIT
	•	SITE_PUBLISH
	•	Same edit rights as EDITOR
	•	Responsible for publishing (when enabled)

STAFF
	•	No site/content permissions

⸻

6. Java API Endpoints (Locked)

Merchant Admin (Write)
	•	GET /tenants/{tenantId}/site/settings
	•	PUT /tenants/{tenantId}/site/settings
	•	GET /tenants/{tenantId}/site/pages/{pageType}
	•	PUT /tenants/{tenantId}/site/pages/{pageType}

Authorization:
	•	SITE_EDIT required for PUT
	•	SITE_EDIT required for GET (or read-only allowed if desired)

⸻

Public Site (Read-only)
	•	GET /public/{tenant}/site/settings
	•	GET /public/{tenant}/site/pages/{pageType}

Notes:
	•	Public endpoints return only published content
	•	Tenant is resolved by domain/slug

⸻

7. Publishing Model (Locked – MVP)

MVP approach
	•	No draft vs publish separation
	•	Updates go live immediately
	•	SITE_PUBLISH action is a no-op or cache purge

Future evolution (explicitly supported)
	•	Draft content stored separately
	•	Admin-only publish promotes draft → published
	•	Public site reads published only

No schema rewrite required to add this later.

⸻

8. Caching & Resilience

Caching (recommended)
	•	Java may cache Payload reads per tenant/page
	•	Cache invalidation triggered on content update

Failure handling
	•	Payload read failure → return last cached content if available
	•	Payload write failure → return error, no partial updates

⸻

9. Audit Logging (Locked)

Every content change must record:
	•	tenantId
	•	userId
	•	action (UPDATE_SITE_SETTINGS, UPDATE_PAGE_HOME, etc.)
	•	Payload document ID
	•	timestamp
	•	changed fields summary

Audit logs live in the platform DB (not Payload).

⸻

10. Security Guarantees
	•	Merchant never sees Payload Admin UI
	•	Merchant never sees Payload IDs or credentials
	•	TenantId cannot be spoofed by client
	•	Field-level access strictly controlled in Java

⸻

11. Explicitly Out of Scope (MVP)
	•	Direct Payload access for merchants
	•	Custom scripts or CSS injection
	•	Page builders
	•	Multi-language content
	•	Content versioning UI

⸻

12. Final Locked Summary
	•	Java is the only gateway to Payload
	•	Payload is used strictly for content storage
	•	Merchant Admin edits content via simple forms
	•	Only allowlisted fields are editable
	•	EDITOR and ADMIN can edit content
	•	Publish is ADMIN-only (future)
	•	Public site reads content via Java APIs

This specification is locked and implementation-ready.